{"id":"d=origam-topic-4292//p=59b2da07bb1a465780a5713b6cb3ed1f","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4292"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["f0c3fe2540664e2bbfa4aca74255d561"],"__file_part":["efea9eb841f84117a43cb2ff9b067355"],"__part_n":["0"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["4292"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-create-a-simple-api/4292"],"title":["How to create a simple API"],"imagesFound":["11"],"imagesDescribed":["11"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/61998b38f8e87b432e3af027ce3731715c4379de.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/56824411524bc539cdae5a3706feb4bdf0f21949.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/ce7f6066dee18e15bafa83859897c226c280aea3.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0c9a57351628e3b091abeb06b138acc67087a1b1.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6a3a62494f76ceaaf305ce02ef5e18b3c321e2b9.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/e89d2c81c195265fc16c763626092191d2db502d.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/054e94792a151767ed94e95b09ccaa5bc0ca7b6e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/59242013445428e7aa2804e0fe78bb69aa65c3fa.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/5d9473b1e0697bbdab335431c05e8fd7ed36b0de.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/145ae915189682a86f73d433417bd08a3e3665a4.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/7bead95d6c06ae8fb555e485d26467a583b63b7d.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":"# How to create a simple API\n\nURL: https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-create-a-simple-api/4292\n\n@vikter (2025-11-06 08:26:17Z):\n   \n This article demonstrates how to create a simple  RESTful API  that makes your data accessible to external applications and services or to internal custom frontend plugins. \n There are four  different API types  \u2013 in ORIGAM called \u201CAPI Pages\u201D \u2013 this text focuses solely on one of these types \u2013 the  Data Page, which provides data in XML or JSON format . \n \n   Note: The API in the model is only used to expose the API of the modeled application externally; work with any external APIs is modeled in the business logic section using  sequential workflows . \n \n \n [!success]- Prerequisites for proceeding \n To follow along, you must meet the following prerequisites: \n \n  Running database server  \n  Running ORIGAM Server  \n  Project created in ORIGAM Architect  \n  Entity with data created  \n \n \n We will perform the following actions: \n \n Retrieve an entire list of items \n Retrieve the details of a specific item from the list \n Update an existing item \n Delete an item \n \n As an example, we will use the simple  task manager from the initial tutorial . We will list all tasks and then work with one of them. \n \n     If you are new to application development or unfamiliar with APIs, you may find the following videos useful: \n \n  API introduction with real-world examples  \n  REST API and HTTP methods  \n \n \n   Introduction \n The API section is one of the five main ORIGAM modeling areas: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/61998b38f8e87b432e3af027ce3731715c4379de.png]\nDescription: The image displays a section of a software development environment, specifically the Model Browser interface. It presents a hierarchical view of components under the node labeled \u0022myapplication.\u0022 The visible categories include \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022User Interface,\u0022 and \u0022Business Logic.\u0022 The \u0022API\u0022 section is highlighted and expanded, indicating it contains a sub-item titled \u0022Web API/Pages.\u0022 This layout suggests a focus on organizing application components for easier navigation and management within the development environment.\n\n\n  \n ORIGAM works with both REST and SOAP APIs and currently supports the following  HTTP methods : \n \n GET \n POST \n PUT \n DELETE \n \n It supports both  JSON  and  XML  formats; in this example, we will use only JSON. In terms of structure, the data in the API is based on a  data structure . \n There are two API privacy options:  private  or  public . Any API starting with  api/public  is preset as public, for other URLs the accessibility as public or restricted routes can be declared in the  UserApiOptions  section of the  appsettings.json  file. In other words, anything not located in  api/public/  is considered private by default, unless explicitly set otherwise. \n In this tutorial, we will create a  public API  \u2014 accessible to anyone once published, but limited by the server accessibility, during development typically the localhost. \n In all cases, we will create a new  Data Page  designed to expose application data: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/56824411524bc539cdae5a3706feb4bdf0f21949.png]\nDescription: The image features a Model Browser interface for an application named \u0022myapplication,\u0022 displaying a hierarchical structure of application components. Visible categories include \u0022Common,\u0022 \u0022Data,\u0022 \u0022User Interface,\u0022 \u0022Business Logic,\u0022 and \u0022API.\u0022 Under \u0022API,\u0022 the submenu titled \u0022Web API/Pages\u0022 is open, showing options to create a \u0022New\u0022 item, which includes \u0022New Group,\u0022 \u0022Repeat New\u0022 (shortcut F12), and various page types: \u0022Workflow Page,\u0022 \u0022Data Page,\u0022 \u0022File Download Page,\u0022 and \u0022Report Page.\u0022 The interface aims to facilitate the organization and management of application pages and groups within the model.\n\n\n  \n When working with APIs, you will usually also need to filter records using  parameters  in the URL \u2014 for example, to specify a particular record using its Id, or to select records only within a certain time range (date from \u2014 date to). This is done using parameters that need to be defined within the API. \n You can learn more about other API Page types in the  documentation . \n   Getting ready to create an API \n   Data structure \n Any API data page requires a  Data Structure  to operate. Before creating the API data page, we\u2019ll first create one. You can name it the same as the main database entity with  _API  suffix. ","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-02T00:00:20"},"vector":[-0.028101716,-0.0077533373,-0.04890129,0.024125079,-0.006749005,-0.022639224,-0.0147780515,-0.0027857395,0.0126851015,0.027276324,-0.016230537,0.011748704,0.017945305,0.008287938,-0.020494377,0.040840823,-0.0070599616,0.020825235,0.026135601,0.024792746,-0.010574724,0.06450113,0.03292835,0.0032389683,0.007915462,0.033523005,-0.036944967,-0.03220845,-0.019558605,-0.016005607,-0.0017298985,-0.039492205,-0.02595034,-0.030631064,-0.02753119,-0.008800624,-0.043368988,-0.03048002,-0.04090084,0.0124481665,0.0081328405,-0.033584222,-0.015833678,0.0045292065,0.005119974,-0.056879323,-0.022084918,0.0061052083,0.030980814,-0.049299873,-0.032330986,0.00088751613,0.009299258,-0.05772978,-0.020183165,0.019785466,-0.0013738574,-0.01769645,-0.07027048,0.052385133,-0.03847121,0.023297897,-0.033196162,-0.011891323,0.021518195,0.011632161,-0.039141763,-0.006082129,-0.020061772,-0.010541479,-0.015564848,0.011142211,-0.07076859,-0.016269745,-0.060607295,-0.024441548,0.026489612,0.02721027,-0.022575326,0.014022443,-0.024446415,-0.016807182,0.03325597,-0.0010512052,0.00076670933,-0.0059500514,-0.03342427,0.07332283,0.028811751,0.028220836,-0.03783321,-0.028668683,0.07710585,-0.06209733,0.00067364966,-0.010789843,0.0047483705,0.024867263,0.008639504,0.02402594,-0.014028984,-0.032827295,-0.03437837